column1: Thise olde gentil Britouns in hir dayes
column3: ¶“In feith, Squier, thou hast thee wel yquit,°
And gentilly° I preise wel thy wit,”°

column1: Rymeyed in hir firste Briton tonge,
Whiche layes with hir instrumentz they songe
column3: So feelingly° thou spekest, sir, I allow’the°

column1: Or elles redden hem for hir plesaunce;
column3: As to my doom,° there is non that is here

column1: And oon of hem have I in remembraunce,
column3: Of° eloquence that shal be thy pere,

column1: Which I shal seyn with good wyl as I kan.
column3: If that thou live; God yeve° thee good chaunce,°

column1: But, sires, by cause I am a burel man,
column3: And in vertu send thee continuaunce!°

column1: At my bigynnyng first I yow biseche,
column3: For of° thy speche I have greet deintee.°

column1: Have me excused of my rude speche.
column3: I have a sone, and, by the Trinitee,
I hadde lever° than twenty pound worth lond,

column1: Thyng that I speke, it moot be bare and pleyn.
column3: Though it right now were fallen in min hond,

column1: I sleep nevere on the Mount of Pernaso,
column3: He° were a man of swich discrecioun°
As that ye been. Fy on possessioun°

column1: Colours ne knowe I none, withouten drede,
column3: But if° a man be vertuous withal.

column1: But swiche colours as growen in the mede,
column3: I have my sone snibbed,° and yet° shal,

column1: Or elles swiche as men dye or peynte.
column3: For he to vertu listeth nat° entende;°

column1: Colours of rethoryk been to me queynte;
column3: But for to pleye at dees,° and to despende,°

column1: My spirit feeleth noght of swich mateere.
column3: And lese° al that he hath, is his usage.°

column1: But if yow list, my tale shul ye heere.
column3: And he hath lever° talken with a page°
